<TEXT>
campbell soup co should have mentioned the 
sodium content of its soups in advertisements that claimed they were 
good for the heart because of being low in fat and cholesterol the 
federal trade commission says 
saying that the companys magazine ads a year ago were false 
misleading or deceptive the ftc issued a complaint thursday 
against campbells which said it would contest the allegation 
the commission also charged that campbells had no substantiation 
for its implied claim that most of its soups make a positive 
contribution to a diet that reduces the risk of heart disease 
healthrelated information is important to consumers and 
advertising is a principal source of that information said 
william macleod head of the commissions bureau of consumer 
protection this is why the commission demands accuracy in 
advertising 
the offending ads ran in magazines in the winter of 1988 and then 
were dropped for a new campaign company spokesman david hackney 
said the decision to end the ads had nothing to do with the 
commissions investigation 
macleod singled out a twopage ad that said campbells soups were 
high in fiber high in calcium when made with milk and low in fat 
and cholesterol 
a serving of regular chicken noodle or new special request 
with onethird less salt is low in fat and has just 15 milligrams 
of cholesterol and thats especially good to know because research 
tells us that a diet low in fat and cholesterol may help reduce the 
risk of some forms of heart disease the ad said 
campbells sells about twothirds of the 22 billion worth of 
soup sold in stores every year 
the commission proposed that campbells be required to disclose 
in its advertising the exact sodium content of any soup having more 
than 500 milligrams per eightounce serving if the company claims 
heart benefits for it 
there was no request that the disclosure say anything about the 
effects of sodium 
many manufacturers and cooks add it to food for better taste 
its in dispute just how much sodium part of ordinary table salt 
is bad 
humans need only 200 milligrams a day but most americans probably 
get 4000 to 6000 milligrams the national academy of sciences said 
in a recent report urging people to hold down intake to somewhere 
between 1100 to 3300 milligrams 
in many people extra salt makes their blood pressure shoot up 
but in others blood pressure remains constant over wide variations 
in salt intake 
hackney said campbell would present experts that would dispute 
any linkage between dietary sodium and high blood pressure we 
stand behind our advertising and dont think its misleading he 
said 
in a later statement from corporate headquarters campbells said 
it is the only major soup manufacturer to list sodium content along 
with other nutritional information on the label 
not counting such variations as its chunky line or its two 
kinds of lowsodium soups campbells makes 70 different condensed 
soups in the familiar redandwhite cans 
macleod declined to say what the commission staff knows about 
their average sodium content but a quick inspection of six on a 
supermarket shelf showed sodium ranging from 710 milligrams in 
turkey vegetable to 910 milligrams in chicken noodle the 
supermarket house brands were similar 
</TEXT>
