<TEXT>
james a baker iii faced a major decision on 
his first working day as secretary of state deciding to evacuate 
the handful of us officials threatened by the spreading civil war 
in afghanistan 
baker remained out of the public eye at the agency on thursday 
but the increased turmoil in kabul required his immediate attention 
the secretarys circumspect day stood in sharp contrast to the 
last change of administration in 1981 when secretary of state 
alexander haig entered the building and boasted that president 
reagan had annointed him the vicar of american foreign policy 
a us official speaking on condition he not be named said 
bakers predecessor george shultz had decided to leave the 
decision on whether to close the us embassy in kabul to the new 
administration baker moved the morning after taking his oath of 
office the official said 
the decision to evacuate the us employees came as the soviets 
continued to pull out troops that have been in the country since 
1979 and as fighting has increased between the promoscow government 
and usbacked rebels battling for control 
although a more formal swearingin ceremony is scheduled for this 
evening at the white house baker had been sworn in privately 
wednesday evening at the state department hours after he was 
confirmed by the senate as president bushs chief adviser on foreign 
policy 
