<TEXT>
you would think that in this barren broadway 
season just about any song and dance celebration sporting music by 
ellington arlen armstrong handy and others would lift the spirits 
but for much of the time thats not the case with black and 
blue the new musical revue that opened thursday at broadways 
minskoff theater its an uneven production that contains flashes of 
sass and expert tap dancing but too often settles for the routine 
responsibility for that predictability lies with claudio segovia 
and hector orezzoli who are credited in the program with conceiving 
and directing this new revue the duo creators of the hit tango 
argentino have staged black and blue with surprisingly little 
style something their earlier show had in abundance 
the musical attempts to recreate the sizzle and snap of the 
cotton club and apollo revues that galvanized harlem audiences in 
1920s 30s and 40s black and blue might work better in a 
nightclub setting in the cavernous minskoff the lack of production 
values are apparent as is the perfunctory quality of henry letangs 
ensemble choreography which seems more las vegas glitz than uptown 
swagger 
excitement is confined mainly to a small group of terrific tap 
dancers mostly in solos duets and trios the tappers include such 
veterans as bunny briggs jimmy slyde ralph brown and lon chaney as 
well as a talented young hoofer named savion glover 
briggs a little man with saucer eyes and an impish smile 
infuses his tap routines with a delicacy that is astonishing he 
embraces ellingtons in a sentimental mood treating the song as 
if it were a partner and creates a joyousness that is hard to 
resist 
slyde gets similar results with stompin at the savoy but 
his style is smoother slicker more like a fred astaire routine 
and how many dancers can skate across the stage in taps 
the best number in the show is another ellington ditty east 
st louis toodleoo with brown and chaney two elder statesman of 
tap showing that age hasnt diminished their love of dance 
most of the singing falls to three formidable ladies ruth 
brown linda hopkins and carrie smith each of these women has her 
moment a showcase to strut her stuff but often their talents are 
not used to best advantage 
miss brown tears up the place in st louis blues and the 
raunchy if i cant sell it ill keep sittin on it but then 
seems uneasy in an overly contrived version of body and soul 
miss smith with the deepest voice this side of vaughan monroe 
shines through two illconceived production numbers one to ive 
got the right to sing the blues it places her on a huge silver 
orb that rolls out on stage and then tilts backwards subjecting the 
audience to a bad case of vertigo the second am i blue has 
her perched on a swing high above the stage while the long train of 
her dress billows to the floor 
miss hopkins may have the most forceful of the three voices but 
she tends to diminish its power by going for the easy laugh and cute 
gesture or phrasing that cuteness mars songs such as cry like a 
baby a raucous big maybelle smith number 
segovia and orezzoli also created the scenery costumes and 
lighting their settings are minimal mostly curtains in various 
shades of red yellow blue and gray but they serve as backdrops 
for the teams striking lighting designs 
the lighting allows for the performers shadows sometimes 
reaching to proscenium to hover over the stage or to be splashed 
on the side walls of the theater these dancing shadows spark im 
confessin that i love you the one ensemble number that really 
utilizes the performers the stage and the production design 
the fine orchestra conducted by leonard oxley is composed of 
expert musicians including sir roland hanna as its principal piano 
soloist 
the best of the recent black musical revues the original 
aint misbehavin and the offbroadway hit one mo time for 
example harnessed an energy that built throughout the entire 
evening black and bllue scatters its resources and could end 
after just about any number in the second act theres no emotional 
payoff instead you have to wait patiently for those marvelous tap 
dancers to come on stage and take over the place 
in other reviews 
howard kissel in the daily news said the show is in a class by 
itself black and blue is closer in spirit to other eras 
he wrote if you listen you hear a dignity an elegance a 
worldliness that stands in great contrast to the aggressiveness and 
desperation that underlie so much of our pop music 
in the new york post clive barnes called the show downright 
terrific it has passion finesse fun and above all style 
but frank rich in the new york times said the show was a weird 
at times diverting crosscultural mishmash 
while bursting with talent worthy of the cotton club or the 
apollo or birdland black and blue looks like the bloated 
nightclub floor shows that used to flourish in decadent latin 
american capitals just before dictatorships collapsed 
</TEXT>
