<TEXT>
the operator of the energy departments 
crippled nuclear weapons plant in south carolina has advocated 
lowering a safety standard that is complicating efforts to reopen 
the plant the chairman of a safety advisory panel said today 
john ahearne chairman of the departments advisory committee on 
nuclear facility safety said ei du pont de nemours amp co has been 
seeking for about three years to establish a scientific 
justification for lowering the minimum standard for judging the 
safety of nuclear reactors 
he said the du pont effort was not directly related to efforts to 
reopen the savannah river plants nuclear reactors which have been 
closed since last year for safety and technical reasons 
the lower standard if adopted would nonetheless make it easier 
to restart the reactors he said 
ahearne said du pont has been trying to make the case that 
the current definition of the worst possible accident at a reactor 
the complete break of a major cooling water pipe was unnecessarily 
strict du ponts research has focused on basing safety judgments on 
the lesser danger posed by a leak in the pipe which would give 
enough warning time to shut the reactor and avert a pipe break 
no du pont officials at savannah river were immediately available 
to comment on ahearnes remarks 
as recently as last december the committee reviewed du ponts 
scientific work and concluded it was a long way from justifying 
the lower safety standard ahearne said 
ahearne in a telephone interview denied a published report that 
he told a senate committee on thursday that the energy department 
was considering reducing the safety standard so it could speed the 
reopening of the k reactor at the savannah river plant which 
has been closed for safety since last april 
he said department safety officials were very very skeptical 
of the proposal which also has been under study for years in the 
civilian nuclear industry he said he told the panel that du pont 
