<TEXT>
the soviet union has bought another 25000 
metric tons of us wheat at subsidized prices the agriculture 
department said friday 
christopher e goldthwait acting general sales manager for the 
departments foreign agricultural service said the wheat was part 
of an authorization of more than 2 million tons under the export 
enhancement program or eep 
goldthwait said the wheat is for shipment for march counting 
some left over from a previous eep arrangement and a newly 
authorized 2 million tons this week the soviets have more than 201 
million tons still available under the program 
with the latest sale the soviet union has bought about 19 
million tons of wheat for delivery in the sixth year of a longterm 
supply agreement which was extended last fall to run through dec 
31 1990 
a metric ton is about 2205 pounds and is equal to 367 bushels 
of wheat the 25000 tons are equal to about 917500 bushels worth 
around 37 million at recent us farm prices 
the eep arrangement allows private exporters to sell wheat and 
other designated commodities to specified countries at reduced 
prices in order to meet foreign competition the exporters then 
collect free government surpluses of grain or other products as 
bonuses or subsidies 
sales for delivery in the sixth year of the agreement also 
included about 102 million tons of corn along with 450000 tons of 
soybeans 128 million tons of soybean meal and 500000 tons of 
grain sorghums 
goldthwait said the 25000 tons of wheat were sold by the peavey 
co which will get subsidy of 2370 per ton or about 65 cents per 
bushel under the eep arrangement 
