<TEXT>
a 36 billion backlog of losses piled up by the 
farmers home administration is not adding to the federal budget 
deficit according to a report friday by the congressional research 
service 
although fmha loan losses are large the budget impact of these 
losses have already been recognized in scaleddown projections for 
future loan repayments the report said the writeoff of these 
delinquent loans per se does not require a budget outlay hence the 
deficit is not affected 
the report said a recent audit by the general accounting office 
another agency of congress showed that fmha over a 40year period 
through 1987 had as much as 36 billion in accumulated deficits that 
will require large sums of congressional funding 
this led some observers to conclude that fmha will likely fuel 
the federal budget deficit by requiring an infusion of cash similar 
to the plight of the savings and loan crisis the report said 
the fmha funds its accumulated losses by borrowing directly from 
the treasury each year the report said the agency asks congress 
for reimbursement of losses that were incurred two years earlier 
for example the budget requests for the 1990 fiscal year that will 
begin oct 1 will be for fiscal 1988 losses 
to date fmha has been reimbursed by annual congressional 
appropriations for virtually all of the 39 billion in loan 
writeoffs that it has recognized through fiscal 1989 the report 
said fmha estimates that nearly 20 billion in loan loss 
reimbursement requests will be submitted over the next several 
years 
the report said that while it may be inaccurate to compare fmha 
losses to the savings and loan situation the magnitude of fmhas 
loan repayment problems should not be diminished 
but it added most budget projections already take into account 
that the most seriously delinquent fmha loans will not be repaid 
therefore unless there were another downturn in the farm economy or 
other economic shock that caused a further deterioration in the 
repayment capacity of fmha borrowers future outlays and the federal 
deficit should not be further affected by loan repayment problems 
the report which was dated jan 18 was written by agricultural 
policy analyst ralph chite of the congressional research services 
food and agriculture section 
as an agency of the agriculture department the fmha is often 
called the governments lender of last resort for farmers who cannot 
qualify for credit elsewhere as of last sept 30 the agency had 
total loans outstanding of about 62 billion 
less than half of the total about 255 billion was owned under 
farm lending programs the balance was for fmha loans for rural 
housing and rural development 
of the total 62 billion in loans about 92 billion were 
delinquent as of last sept 30 the farm delinquencies represented 
83 billion of that amount the fmha has sent collection notices to 
thousands of delinquent borrowers telling them to make arrangements 
with the agency for repayments or face the possibility of forced 
sales or foreclosures 
