arthur marshall whose benign humor endeared him to 
an audience of millions in half a lifetime of radio and tv 
broadcasts died friday at the age of 78 the british broadcasting 
corp said 
marshalls very english style with its joy in the humor of words 
and the eccentricities of people made him a household name 
he died in his sleep after a long fight against cancer at his 
home in the south devon village of christow near exeter south of 
london the bbc said 
marshall was also a journalist contributing to the new statesman 
magazine for 46 years until what he called the discontinuance of 
his whimsical jottings in 1981 
in 1978 he joined the popular bbctv word game call my bluff 
where he and other panelists tried to fool each other with fake 
definitions of obscure words 
his round bespectacled face smiled mischievously from millions 
of television sets around the country each week 
his wit and gentility had enormous appeal bbc official james 
moir said friday 
program host robert robinson called him rotund and cherubic 
one of the most likeable men i have ever met 
fellow panelist frank muir said he was an extraordinary man 
extremely intelligent with that old english tradition of polite 
sentimental humor his was the true alternative comedy in an era 
of television humor which has become aggressive impertinent and 
fairly offensive 
marshall reared in southwest london attended the respected 
oundle school and returned there as a teacher of french and german 
from 193154 except for the war years when he worked in 
intelligence 
his classroom experiences formed the basis of much of his humor 
and he found early success with sketches impersonating elderly 
schoolmistresses 
