trans world airlines is liable for civil damages 
to 3000 former flight attendants who were replaced when they went 
on strike in 1986 a federal judge has ruled 
were ecstatic plaintiffs attorney robert balfour said 
friday 
us district judge ilana rovner set the stage for a hearing on 
damages with her ruling thursday no date for the hearing was set 
but balfour said attorneys for both sides would meet with ms rovner 
on wednesday 
the telephone went unanswered at the airlines corporate offices 
in mount cisco ny after business hours and no spokesmen were 
available at twas st louis office 
the flight attendants 1986 classaction lawsuit seeks 80 
million from the airline contending twa hindered their efforts to 
find work with other carriers during and after a 1986 strike 
the lawsuit sought both compensatory and punitive damages but 
the judge denied the request to seek a punitive award balfour said 
however he called 80 million still a realistic figure 
more than 5700 members of new yorkbased independent federation 
of flight attendants struck twa on feb 13 1986 and were told 
their jobs would be filled by others 
under the airline deregulation act of 1978 furloughed or fired 
workers with at least four years experience must be given 
preference over newcomers by other carriers the law required twa to 
give the striking attendants letters certifying they had such 
experience and were eligible for first consideration by other 
airlines 
the flight attendants lawsuit contends twa refused to issue such 
letters to strikers on grounds the move would jeopardize their jobs 
at twa it says the airline also refused to advise the attendants 
they were eligible for preferential hiring 
twa maintained that stance when the strike was over the lawsuit 
says 
when no contract agreement had been reached with twa by may 17 
1986 the union made an unconditional offer to return to work but 
just 197 of the strikers got their jobs back 
nearly 1300 attendants crossed picket lines according to court 
records others found jobs at other airlines or left the industry 
while the flight attendants union was not involved in the court 
action officials were pleased with ms rovners ruling union 
spokeswoman joan wages said friday from new york 
