<TEXT>
look to your pawns and pieces human the 
30thranked chess player in the united states is a machine 
deep thought a computer put together by graduate students as a 
hobby kind of thing came out of nowhere to beat hitech the 
worlds toprated chessplaying program at a computer chess 
tournament in november 
certainly a year ago no one thought this was possible vince 
mccambridge an international master and spokesman for the us 
chess federation said friday 
it brings the specter of a computer world chess champion by the 
end of the century closer to reality said mccambridge who has 
played deep thought to a draw 
hitech the erstwhile champion was one of many formidable 
opponents deep thought beat at the association of computing 
machinery tournament in orlando fla winning its ranking as the 
30th best chess player human or mechanical in the united states 
until that november tournament hitech built by carnegie mellon 
university professor hans berliner had been the games best 
electronic player 
deep thought built by five carnegie mellon graduate students 
lacks the chess knowledge that berliner programmed into hitech but 
more than compensates by being almost six times faster at sorting 
through the myriad possibilities for moving pieces on the board 
its speed allows it to look more moves ahead in the game 
berliner was out of town and could not be reached for comment a 
university spokeswoman said 
by achieving a rating of 2551 under the us chess federation 
system deep thought also won the fredkin intermediate prize for 
becoming the first machine to surpass the 2500 barrier hitech ranks 
just above 2400 world champion gary kasparov of the soviet union 
by comparison ranks above 2800 
the 10000 prize money to be awarded in detroit in august will 
be shared among deep thoughts five creators led by computer 
science student fenghsiung hsu 
hsu who designed the silicon guts of the computer said he 
intends to replace the two microprocessors that power it with eight 
microprocessors to make deep thought even faster the machine can 
now analyze 700000 board positions per second compared to 120000 
for hitech hsu said 
now that the students have won the second of three prizes to be 
offered by by massachusetts institute of technology professor edward 
fredkin hsu has not ruled out a shot at the one remaining 
100000 to the first machine to beat the reigning international 
champion 
the first fredkin prize 5000 went to two bell labs scientists 
in 1981 for creating the first computer to achieve the status of 
chess master 
deep thought is all the more impressive because the five students 
lacked the financial backing of other artificial intelligence 
research programs mccambridge said 
there are a number of other programs at bell labs los alamos 
labs and the hitech project which are backed by enormous research 
money he said the deep thought project was really done as a 
hobby kind of thing by a few guys 
deep thought received 5000 from the defense department said 
team member thomas anatharaman the five students who also include 
michael browne murray campbell and andreas nowatzyk scraped 
together donated funds to travel to chess tournaments he said 
hitech in contrast got at least 20000 for components said 
cmu spokeswoman anne watzman 
of the five deep thought creators campbell is the best chess 
player holding expert status which is not strong at all said 
browne 
and the person who programmed it has difficulty keeping his 
moves on the board so deep thought was purely an engineering 
approach browne said 
at the software toolworks open in long beach calif in 
november the machine beat international masters jeremy silman and 
alex fishbein and played mccambridge to a draw 
its only defeat came against walter browne who holds the world 
chess federations highest rank grandmaster and is a sixtime us 
chess federation champion 
it was the most impressive achievement ever for a computer 
said mccambridge who for a time had an advantage in his game with 
deep thought 
i relaxed when i was winning he said it never gets tired 
and it never gives up 
</TEXT>
