<TEXT>
after 27 years of fighting the sovietbacked 
ethiopian government and separatist rebels in eritrea province say 
theyre ready to negotiate a settlement of africas longest war 
but many obstacles remain in the way namely finding a suitable 
mediator and overcoming the deep divisions among the rebel groups 
themselves 
the conflict has claimed hundreds of thousands of lives driven 
nearly a eritrean million refugees westward into neighboring sudan 
and compounded the suffering from the regions devastating famine 
the rebels who scored major battlefield victories last spring 
and reported new gains in late december say they are tightening 
their siege around a key governmentheld city while bracing for a 
new ethiopian offensive 
the guerrillas led by the dominant eritrean peoples liberation 
front eplf which along with other rebel factions has offices in 
rome control about threefourths of the territory the government 
holds most of the major cities 
eritrea is situated on the strategic horn of africa which 
overlooks the red sea approach to the suez canal as well a key water 
route to the oil fields of saudi arabia slightly larger than 
pennsylvania eritrea has a 1000mile coastline along the red sea 
across from southern saudi arabia 
a former italian colony eritrea was federated with ethiopia in 
1952 under a ussponsored resolution in the united nations the 
eritreans battle for independence began in 1961 emperor haile 
selassie annexed the territory in 1962 
selassie was overthrown in 1974 by the military that established 
todays marxist government he died in detention in 1975 
as the conflict has worn one the eritreans have built a 
selfreliant society the rebels who receive no significant outside 
military or financial support have built an array of schools 
hospitals and workshops some of them underground or in hillside 
caverns to avoid detection from the air that contribute both to 
the war effort and the needs of the general population 
in march 1987 the main secessionist groups adopted a 
constitution and a national program 
in interviews in rome the eritreans acknowledged that 
differences in ideology and strategy have led to fighting among 
themselves but they all declared a willingness to negotiate with 
ethiopia they contended however that president mengistu haile 
maniam of ethiopia was not sincere in his expressed desire for a 
settlement 
in particular the eritreans condemned mengistus meeting in his 
capital addis ababa in late december with what ethiopia described 
as a delegation of the eritrean liberation front the elf the 
oldest of the rebel groups has split into several rival factions 
over the years 
the delegation reportedly agreed to have the province of 35 
million people divided into two autonomous regions one for moslems 
and the other for christians according to addis ababa radio the 
ethiopian politburo accepted that idea and sent a proposal to 
parliament or shengo for final approval in june 
the eritreans interviewed in rome maintained that those who met 
with mengistu were former rebels who now live in arab countries of 
the persian gulf and do not represent any of the legitimate 
organizations 
they are traitors said asefau bariamikael vice president of 
the elfnational council 
this is just an attempt by ethiopia to create divisions and 
shows their lack of seriousness in confronting the problem said 
solomon kinfe an eplf fighter and representative here 
ethiopia has always tried to divide eritrea on basis of 
religion but religion has always been an element of unification 
said taha nur of the elfunited organization 
still all three groups said they are willing to talk through a 
mediator and that the united nations should reopen the eritrean 
issue 
we are ready to participate actively in solving the problem 
politically and ready to negotiate with the ethiopian government 
without preconditions nur said 
previously some of the groups had said they would negotiate only 
on condition that independence would be discussed 
once we sit down then we will make our proposal for complete 
independence bariamikael of the elfnational council said if 
they ethiopians dont want to hear it beforehand well just say 
it later but we wont change our mind about complete independence 
kinfe said the eplf continues to demand that the conflict be 
settled by a referendum offering eritreans three choices 
independence regional autonomy or a return to federation 
</TEXT>
