<TEXT>
although ideology is one factor dividing the rebel groups the 
political outlook of each of them remains vague and none has set 
forth any ideological platform on which they would govern eritrea 
the dominant eplf is considered the most leftleaning and is 
widely considered marxistoriented the group itself rejects any 
political identification tag saying it is neither marxist nor 
imperialist and has no superpower backing 
margherita boniver a socialist member of the italian parliament 
who has been to eritrea said some of the groups consider the 
eplf fanatics but the eplf people are very well informed about the 
international scene and after 27 years of fighting i doubt they 
would opt for a marxist society 
bariamikael of the elfnational council said we all want 
eritrea as a democratic nation represented by parliament and 
different parties 
the ethiopian government has not recently stated its position on 
negotiations with the rebels telephone calls by the associated 
press to officials at the ethiopian embassy in rome were not 
returned however in a document issued in july the government said 
it was ready to negotiate on the basis of the new constitution for 
regional autonomy in eritrea but ruled out independence 
sudans ambassador in rome ibrahim ayoub confirmed that 
ethiopia approached his government last year and asked for its 
mediation sudan agreed as part of an effort to settle all conflicts 
in the horn of africa and is seeking to clarify the position of 
both parties ayoub said sudan shares the west shore of the red 
sea with eritrea and egypt 
while the elfunited organization has backed mediation by sudan 
the eplf has rejected the sudanese because of their moslemdominated 
governments war against christian guerrillas in southern sudan 
the eplf prefers that mediation efforts are better undertaken 
by third parties that are not in any way involved in the conflicts 
in the region the eplf said in a statement on jan 17 
