<TEXT>
federal transportation officials have decided 
the 1990 fueleconomy standards should remain at the previous years 
265 miles per gallon says a private autosafety advocacy group 
that wants a higher ceiling 
the transportation department and national highway traffic safety 
administration would neither confirm nor deny thursdays assertion 
by the washingtonbased center for auto safety 
the two agencies administer the corporate average fuel economy 
or cafe standards 
meanwhile transportation secretarydesignate samuel skinner said 
he has yet to form a judgment on fuel economy 
center director clarence ditlow said he learned of the decison 
from sources in the transportation departments rulemaking office 
the energy department general motors corp and chrysler corp 
he disclosed the 265 mpg figure in a letter asking president 
bush to intervene in favor of a tighter fueleconomy sandard 
the standard would not be formally set until the agency published 
a notice in the federal register the governments record of 
official actions 
neither the transportation department nor its subsidiary agency 
the national highway traffic safety administration would comment on 
the assertion 
the fueleconomy law was adopted in 1975 to reduce gasoline 
consumption at a time of rapidly rising oil prices and requires 
automakers to design the mix of vehicles in their fleets so that the 
average meets or betters the fuelconsumption standard 
the law set a goal of 275 mpg beginning in 1985 however the 
law also allowed the government to reduce that if the higher level 
would harm automakers or if it was technologically difficult to 
attain 
if transportation officials failed to act the standard would 
revert to 275 mpg a level gm and ford motor co have said is 
impossible for them to meet without layoffs at bigcar plants 
skinner said at a hearing thursday before the senate environment 
and public works committee that the administration was committed to 
an aggressive environmental program and that the fueleconomy 
standards would be a key ingredient in that program 
i dont consider myself in a position to have prejudged that 
issue at all he said 
the standard was set at 18 mpg for 1978 cars rose gradually to 
275 mpg in 1985 and then was lowered to 26 mpg in 1986 at the 
request of some of the automakers it remained at 26 mpg through the 
1988 model year 
the 265 mpg level for 1990 is within the range of 26 mpg to 267 
mpg gm said it could live with 
ford said a 265 mpg level would be appropriate but called for 
changes that would bring the fueleconomy law more in line with 
todays market and economic conditions 
chrysler did not return calls thursday but has said previously it 
could meet the 275 mpg goal set by the law 
