<TEXT>
federal prosecutors offered a 
pleabargain deal to drexel burnham lamberts senior junkbond 
trader michael milken two weeks ago but his lawyers rejected it 
immediately and vowed to fight them in court sources familiar with 
the discussions said today 
the sources who spoke on condition they not be identified said 
milkens defense team did not initiate the meeting with manhattan 
us attorney rudolph giulianis office 
but the contact marked the first time both sides have discussed a 
possible bargain since drexel and milken were embroiled in the wall 
street corruption scandal in late 1986 by nowimprisoned speculator 
ivan f boesky 
milken head of drexels highyield junk bond trading desk in 
beverly hills calif is one of the most dynamic and wealthy 
financiers in the country he is largely credited with vaulting 
drexel into a securities superpower 
drexel capitulated to prosecutors last month and agreed to plead 
guilty to six felonies pay 650 million in fines fire milken and 
cooperate in the governments case against him 
the 42yearold financier is facing asyet unfiled fraud and 
racketeering charges that carry enormous prison terms and financial 
penalties 
the us attorneys office requested a meeting one of the 
sources familiar with the recent contact said milkens attorneys 
went to the meeting the us attorney made a proposal and it was 
rejected 
aides to giuliani said they could not comment on whether such a 
meeting took place but it is not uncommon for targets of 
racketeering indictments to discuss possible settlement discussions 
before the charges are filed 
milken spokesman kenneth lerer also declined to comment on the 
meeting but said in a statement there are no discussions going on 
between the us attorneys office and mike milkens attorneys no 
discussions whatsoever 
for the past 27 months mikes position has remained unchanged 
he will vigorously fight any charges brought against him and his 
lawyers are preparing his defense 
it was unclear what giuliani offered milken to induce him to 
settle he has maintained he did nothing wrong and a turnaround at 
this point would mark a stunning reversal by a major target in what 
has become the biggest securities fraud case in history 
the wall street journal quoting unidentified sources reported 
today that prosecutors said milken would have to plead guilty to two 
felonies with a maximum fiveyear penalty for each count 
but the paper said the deal didnt include immunity for milkens 
brother lowell another senior drexel aide who also is facing 
probable indictment milkens associates said thursday it was 
unlikely he would strike a plea bargain despite the enormous 
pressure he is facing to change his mind 
court papers revealed wednesday that terms of the settlement 
require drexel to dismiss milken and withhold the 1988 compensation 
due him estimated at 200 million his lawyers said the terms 
amount to an outrageous disgraceful and illegal punishment which 
they indicated would be challenged in court 
for milken the crisis hes facing represents far more than loss 
of a job with a personal wealth estimated by forbes magazine at 
800 million and an undisputed knack for making money he can 
survive the loss financially 
but the accusations against him have cast a cloud over a 
remarkable career that revolves around his virtually singlehanded 
creation of the market in highyield highrisk junk bonds 
they also have brought attention and sympathy from the many who 
know milken as a devoted family man attentive friend and donor of 
millions of dollars to charity 
their portrayal stands in sharp contrast to the portrayal of 
milken by government investigators as a scheming manipulative 
arrogant and greedy trader who colluded with boesky to violate a 
range of securities laws 
my sense of things is this is a man who thinks he has done 
nothing to blacken his familys name and thats important to him 
