<TEXT>
britains merchandise deficit narrowed more sharply 
than expected to 166 billion pounds or 294 billion in december 
the government said friday providing further evidence that the 
countrys overheated economy is slowing down 
the news eased fears that british interest rates would be pushed 
higher the pound surprisingly rallied to 17688 following the 
1130 am report but finished the day lower at 17655 down from 
17730 late thursday 
stock prices surged and the financial timesstock exchange 
100share index rose 461 points or 24 percent to close at 
20059 
despite the december improvement britains trade deficit for the 
year more than doubled to 2034 billion pounds or 36 billion and 
the countrys trade picture was much worse than the conservative 
governments chancellor of the exchequer nigel lawson has forecast 
the 1988 deficit was attacked by opposition labor member of 
parliament bryan gould who serves as his partys trade spokesman 
these figures complete the worst year in our trading history they 
also show that any prospect of improvement in 1989 looks very 
remote 
john smith who serves as the labor partys spokesman on treasury 
matters called the deficit the awful legacy of last years 
taxcutting budget he said it was being made worse by lawsons 
reliance on interest rates to head off inflationary pressure 
the december narrowing came as exports rose 3 percent and imports 
held steady the department of trade and industry said 
the financial markets had been expecting a deficit of 149 
billion pounds 264 billion 
the narrowing indicates a slowdown in economic growth and should 
help to reduce the pressure on the government to signal the 
commercial banks to raise their base lending rates from their 
current 13 percent level said ian harwood a british economist at 
the london investment firm warburg securities 
the news should prove more bearish for the pound in the longer 
run harwood said 
this pound rally is just a kneejerk reaction he said 
people are going to be increasingly saying that 13 percent is 
the peak for base rates he said 
the seasonally adjusted deficit for december compared with a 
revised deficit of 187 billion pounds in november and a deficit of 
124 billion pounds in december 1987 the department said 
with decembers invisible trade which covers services overseas 
investment earnings and official transfer payments estimated to be 
in surplus by 400 million pounds britains current account showed a 
deficit of 126 billion pounds in december compared with a revised 
deficit of 147 billion pounds in november and a deficit of 802 
million pounds in december 1987 
the markets had expected the current account deficit to come to 
between 11 billion pounds and 18 billion pounds 
exports totaled 712 billion pounds in december up from 691 
billion pounds in november 
imports totaled 878 billion pounds in december little changed 
from 877 billion pounds in november 
britains 1988 merchandise trade deficit of 2034 billion pounds 
compared with a deficit of 1016 billion pounds in 1987 
the 1988 current account was 1427 billion pounds compared with 
a deficit of 269 billion pounds a year earlier 
the 1988 current account deficit was well above lawsons forecast 
of 13 billion pounds 
