<TEXT>
as americas automobile dealers gather for 
their annual convention many of them are wondering whether 
washington will take action that could cause prices of popular 
sportutility vehicles and vans will soar 
more than 20000 dealers and others connected with the industry 
get together this weekend through tuesday for the 72nd national 
automobile dealers association convention 
the group will install its new president for 1989 ron tonkin of 
ron tonkin dealerships in portland ore tonkin not known to mince 
words will take office at the close of the convention tuesday and 
is expected to issue a strong call for increased unity among the 
dealers to stand up against the automakers 
united the dealers have more net worth than general motors by 
far he said in a preconvention interview our job is to 
harness that horsepower 
but on the minds of many dealers is a proposal for the treasury 
department to boost the tariff on imported sportutility vehicles 
and some vans to 25 percent of their cost 
us manufacturers support and overseas companies oppose the 
move which could limit the influx of foreignmade versions of the 
hotselling vehicles 
earlier this month the chairmen of general motors corp ford 
motor co and chrysler corp asked treasury secretary nicholas f 
brady in an unusual joint letter to uphold a customs service 
recommendation that would classify sportutility vehicles and some 
other vehicles as trucks that would make the vehicles subject to a 
25 percent tariff instead of the 25 percent fee charged on imported 
cars 
the executives gms roger b smith fords donald petersen and 
chryslers lee iacocca said if the increased fee is not charged it 
would cause substantial harm to the us motor vehicle industry 
deprive the us treasury of several hundred million dollars in 
anticipated tariff revenues and unleash a long battle in the courts 
and in congress to restore a clear and consistent rule 
the dealers feel differently 
auto dealers increasingly are diversifying their product lines 
ford chevrolet and dodge dealers for instance more frequently 
offer imported cars and trucks as a hedge against a downturn in the 
us industry and to lure more customers to their showrooms 
many of the foreign automakers produce sportutility vehicles 
similar to the american jeeps prices of the imported versions range 
from less than 8495 for a suzuki samurai to more than 35800 for 
the range rover from england 
the american international automobile dealers association said 
imposing the 25percent tariff would harm its 9000 members and the 
public the organization claims the tariff will add an average 
2500 to the cost of each imported van or sportutility vehicle 
which make up about 18 percent of total import sales and about 30 
percent of the profits of dealers who sell them 
the group and some dealers also have speculated that if the 
tariff is approved the big three us automakers wont be able to 
resist the opportunity to raise their prices somewhat less than 25 
percent to increase profits 
</TEXT>
