<TEXT>
an official at the new york cotton exchange 
gleefully displays a handful of buttons the chicago board of trade 
once distributed to promote its range of interestrate futures 
products 
the buttons read cbot trading opportunities from 30 years to 
30 days an inscription rendered ironic by the sweeping federal 
undercover investigation of alleged fraud at the chicago board of 
trade and the chicago mercantile exchange 
i understand these are going to become very valuable the 
official says as he stashes the buttons in a desk drawer 
similar wry humor can be found among traders of gold and silver 
futures as they leave the floor of new yorks commodity exchange 
whaddaya wearin a wire one trader asks a reporter who is 
gathering reactions to the chicago scandal 
please speak into the microphone says another eliciting 
chuckles from his fellow traders as the elevator door slides shut 
pit traders as a rule are a cocky bunch their thick skins and 
swaggers an essential defense in a profession that rewards steely 
nerves and can ruin the nervous 
but their wisecracks about the chicago probe mask a fear on the 
new york futures exchanges that whatever comes out of the 
investigation will be bad news for the entire futures industry 
i dont see anything funny about it said a midlevel 
employee of one of the five exchanges that operate on the 8th floor 
of 4 world trade center its frightening 
the east coast exchanges the coffee sugar amp cocoa exchange 
the commodity exchange the new york cotton exchange the new york 
futures exchange and the new york mercantile exchange cannot 
escape the shadow of chicagos futures markets which are the 
worlds largest and account for about threequarters of all the 
futures contracts traded in the united states 
the new york exchanges trade some products like crude oil 
platinum frozen orange juice coffee and cotton that arent traded 
in chicago but they operate in same way with traders facing off in 
pits and using a 140yearold system of shouts and hand signals to 
trade contracts for future delivery of commodities 
one trader said that in the wake of the first reports of the 
chicago investigation which surfaced a little more than a week ago 
traders in new york have grown more wary of their associates 
although no similar probe has been revealed in their own markets 
he said they also feared the prices of seats on the new york 
exchanges would tumble as they did in chicago sharply reducing the 
cash value of membership but panic selling of seats did not spread 
east 
exchange seats are traded as commodities and held as investments 
more importantly they give their holders the right to enter the 
trading pits where they can observe price movements firsthand and 
are in the best position to profit from those changes 
the chicago probe has turned a spotlight on the longstanding 
tradition of dual trading which allows pit traders to trade on 
behalf of customers and for their own accounts provided they 
execute the customer orders first 
critics say dual trading is easily abused in certain market 
conditions an unscrupulous trader can switch to his own account a 
profitable trade he originally made on a customers behalf then 
execute the customers order again at a smaller profit than the 
customer should have received 
but exchange officials say the right to trade for ones own 
account while also executing orders for brokerage firms is what 
draws independent speculators to the pits increasing the number of 
pit traders and creating liquid markets 
the potential outcome of the chicago investigation that new york 
exchange officials fear most is new legislation that would restrict 
the traditional openoutcry trading method and outlaw dual trading 
the worst thing that could happen would be for there to turn 
out to be a massive widespread tradingimpropriety problem in 
chicago said alan j brody president of the commodity exchange 
if that be the case and i cross my fingers and hope thats 
not the case the worst result would be that it would cast a shadow 
over the entire industry which includes us in new york and we wind 
up facing regulatory proposals 
brody said dual trading has made the us futures markets the 
most liquid markets in the world 
i would hate to see us throw out all that in the face of what i 
hope not to be a real widespread problem he said 
</TEXT>
